recalls.Summary: VOLKSWAGEN IS RECALLING CERTAIN MODEL YEAR 2009 AND 2010 PASSENGER CARS MANUFACTURED BETWEEN SEPTEMBER 2008 AND AUGUST 2009.  THE WIRING HARNESS OF A TEMPERATURE SENSOR IN THE DIRECT SHIFT GEARBOX (DSG) MAY HAVE CONNECTOR WIRES THAT WERE INSUFFICIENTLY CRIMPED.  WITH INSUFFICIENTLY CRIMPED CONNECTOR WIRES, A TEMPERATURE SENSOR HAS THE POTENTIAL TO FALSELY DETECT A HIGH GEARBOX OIL TEMPERATURE, CAUSING THE TRANSMISSION TO ABRUPTLY SHIFT TO NEUTRAL.  IF THIS HAPPENS, THE SELECTOR LEVER POSITION INDICATOR WITHIN THE INSTRUMENT PANEL WILL FLASH.  IN ADDITION, THE "DEPRESS BRAKE PEDAL" INDICATOR LIGHT WILL BE ILLUMINATED, ALERTING THE DRIVER TO APPLY THE BRAKES.
recalls.Consequence: THE ABRUPT SHIFT TO NEUTRAL COULD LEAD TO A CRASH WITHOUT WARNING.
recalls.Remedy: VOLKSWAGEN WILL REPROGRAM THE TRANSMISSION CONTROL MODULE WITH UPDATED SOFTWARE FREE OF CHARGE.  THE RECALL BEGAN ON OCTOBER 20, 2009.  OWNERS MAY CONTACT VOLKSWAGEN AT 1-800-822-8987.
recalls.Notes: VW RECALL NO. 37E3/S7 & AUDI RECALL NO. 37E5/J7. OWNERS MAY ALSO CONTACT THE NATIONAL HIGHWAY TRAFFIC SAFETY ADMINISTRATION'S VEHICLE SAFETY HOTLINE AT 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), OR GO TO HTTP://WWW.SAFERCAR.GOV .

complaints.summary: The seatbelt is failing as it does not retract back into its holder and I am uncertain as to how safe and effective it is. Note that I have not done anything to cause this damage to it, it is through use and time. Volkswagen Group should approve fixes to it without additional cost to the customer.

under emergency braking at around 70mph all 4 wheels locked up and abs/traction lights illuminated on dash. Caused a minor accident and flat spot on all 4 tires. ABS did not work. This is a know recall for 2009 models of the same vehicle. I replicated the issue a second time at a slower speed on a secluded road with the same results. There are numerous complaints about the same situation on this and other model VW cars of this year all over the internet forums. The ABS module was diagnosed as defective by mechanic shop.

About a month ago, while driving , the abs light, brake light and ESP light came on. After about 2 weeks of troubleshooting, a local mechanic troubleshot the issues to a faulty ABS module. After many phone calls with my local VW dealership I was able to set an appointment for a diagnostic. They determined " Diag ABS system no communication advised on replacement module". The module costing $2,886.04 in parts and labor. With the part not in stock and the dealership saying  " no way of knowing when we'll get one in". Over 130,000 VW's same year and model have had this same issue and been recalled but for some reason my vehicle doesn't have a recall on this vin. Both the VW dealership and VW customer care refuse to do anything. I believe this vehicle like many others were missed or ignored during the recall. My vehicle brakes have been sticking and have locked on me once already in the last month while driving. It is a safety hazard to drive.

Steering lock mechanism has broke twice. Key cannot be removed from steering lock causing it to run and not able to turn off. Once car eventually can be turned off or dies you can no longer remove the key or start the car.

The contact owns a 2010 Volkswagen GTI. The contact stated while driving at various speeds, the check engine warning light illuminated and the vehicle started jerking and failed to properly accelerate while depressing the accelerator pedal. The vehicle was examined by an independent mechanic who diagnosed that the intake manifold was faulty and needed to be replaced. The vehicle was not yet repaired. The manufacturer was notified of the failure. The local dealer was not contacted. The failure mileage was 67,000.

WITH NO PROBLEMS. NEXT MORNING WOULDN'T START. WITH 59,500 MILES I WAS STOCKED. HAD THE CODES READ COILS, SPARK PLUGS, SO I CHANGED THEM. STILL DIDN'T START. 3 DAY LATER, (SHE'S GARAGE KEPT) AND STARTED UP. WELL IN THE LAST 6 MONTH'S IT HAS DONE THE SAME THING 9 TIMES ON THE FREEWAY, 4 TIMES IN THE CITY. TOOK IT TO VW DEALERSHIP THEY READ CODES P0087 WITCH IS LOW PRESSURE FUEL PUMP, FUEL PUMP CONTROL MODULE, FUEL FILTER. SO BUYING ALL NEW PARTS, I GOT FUEL PUMP CONTROL MODULE & FUEL FILTER AT VW DEALERSHIP, FUEL PUMP OVER THE INTERNET ALL NEW PARTS. THE VW PARTS MANAGER TOLD ME THAT VW HAS HAD PROBLEMS WITH CONTROL MODULE ON OTHER MODELS, I THINK HE SAID THAT THEY WERE RECALLED ON JETTA'S, GOLF'S AND VW HAS UPDATED THE FUEL PUMP CONTROL MODULE ON MY 2010 VW GTI 2.0 TURBO 3OR4 TIMES. I ASKED HOW DO I KNOW IF I'M BUYING UPDATED VERSION OR NOT, HE POINTED OUT THE DIFFERENT PART NUMBERS AND SAID YOUR GOOD TO GO. I YOUTUBE VIDEO OF R & R FUEL PUMP, FUEL PUMP CONTROL MODULE, AND FUEL FILTER. MY CAR RAN GREAT FOR 20.5 MILES, STARTING IT UP TWO DAYS LATER AT HOME, I'M LETTING IT WARM UP THE MOTOR FOR A FEW MINUTES AND JUST QUIT AGAIN WOULDN'T START UP. THEN I FIND OUT THERE'S A UPDATED & UPGRADED FUEL PUMP CONTROL MODULE THAT'S HAS 32 AMPS. GOING TO THE FUEL PUMP, WIRES, DEVICE, CLIPS FOR $699.00 AFTER I SPENT $500.00 ON THE PARTS INSTALLED. MY POINT IS THAT SOMEONE WHO IS NOT SMART ENOUGH, STRONG ENOUGH, AND ROAD CONDITIONS VARY MAY NOT GET TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD WITH NO POWER STEERING, POWER BRAKES, EVERYTHING ON A CAR QUITS. HOPE NOBODY GETS HURT/ KILLED.  *TR

DURING MODERATE ACCELERATION, ENGINE CUTS POWER, EPC LIGHT AND CHECK ENGINE LIGHT COMES ON. VEHICLE GOES INTO LIMP MODE, AND ENGINE WILL NOT TURN MORE THAN 3000 RPM, AND HAS NO POWER TO ACCELERATE. ENGINE DEVELOPS MISFIRES AND IDLES VERY ROUGHLY. ENGINE MAY STALL. TURNING KEY OFF AND BACK ON DOES NOT REMEDY THE PROBLEM. DISCONNECTING THE BATTERY WILL TURN THE EPC AND CHECK ENGINE LIGHTS OFF, BUT UNDER NEXT MODERATE ACCELERATION, EPC AND CHECK ENGINE LIGHTS COME BACK ON, AND PROBLEMS COME BACK. CHECK ENGINE DTC CODES RANGE FROM MISFIRES TO SYSTEM TOO LEAN AND AIR INTAKE LEAKS, AND FOR ACCELERATOR/THROTTLE POSITION SENSOR B MALFUNCTIONS. THESE PROBLEMS HAVE HAPPENED MULTIPLE TIMES IN TRAFFIC ON THE INTERSTATE AND IN THE CITY. THE VEHICLE HAS STALLED AT STOP SIGNS AND TRAFFIC LIGHTS. IT HAS ALSO STALLED DURING ACCELERATION. THIS PROBLEM STARTED HAPPENING ON AUGUST 6TH 2019 AND HAS CONTINUED TO HAPPEN.
REAR MAIN SEAL FAILS UNDER 60K MILES HAPPEN TO A LOT OF 2.0T ENGINES.  VOLKSWAGEN SHOULD PROVIDE EXTENDED WARRANTY

CAR JUMPS AND STUDDERS AND THE ENGINE WANTS TO SHUT DOWN SINCE IT CANT ACCELERATE OR SHIFT HIGHER, RPMS GO DOWN TO POINT OF CAR STALLING.

THERE HAS BEEN A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT THE EPC WITH A RECOMMEND FIX. THE SIX GOLD PINS WERE PUT IN TO REPLACE THE ORIGINAL ONES WHICH WORKED FOR SOME TIME BUT FAILED AGAIN. THANKFULLY I DID NOT HAVE MY TWO VERY SMALL CHILDREN WITH ME.

THE TIMING CHAIN TENSIONER SLIPPED AND BLEW THE CAMS.  THE CLUTCH WAS ALSO BAD.  EVERY PERSON I TALKED TO WHEN I HAD TO BUY A NEW ENGINE KNEW THAT VW GTI OR GOLFS HAD THIS NOTORIOUS ISSUE. TAKATA RECALL    2010 VOLSKWAGEN GTI DID NOT FALL UNDER THE TAKATA RECALL VIN NUMBERS, HOWEVER MY FRONT LEFT AIRBAG IS NEEDING A COMPLETE REPLACEMENT. IT WAS FOUND WITH THE FOLLOWING FAULT CODE:    "CODE B10001B, DRIVE AIRBAG IGNITER RESISTANCE TOO HIGH // INSPECT PLUG"    THOUGH THE SAME EXACT MAKE/MODEL/YEAR OF MY VEHICLE FALL UNDER THE TAKATA RECALL I WAS TOLD BY VOLKSWAGEN THAT MY VEHICLE'S VIN DID NOT FALL UNDER THE RECALL. I FIND IT UNLIKELY THAT A VEHICLE MADE JUST A FEW DAYS AFTER MINE COULD FALL UNDER THIS RECALL, BUT MINE DOES NOT. I HAVE AN EXAMPLE OF THIS AIRBAG FROM TAKATA FAILING, BUT AM EXPECTED TO PAY FOR THE REPAIR MYSELF.

THIS FAILURE USUALLY OCCURS JUST AFTER THE VW WARRANTY EXPIRES ON THE CAR.  VW HAS MADE A 2017 UPGRADE MANIFOLD TO FIX THIS PROBLEM BUT THEY REFUSE TO RECALL THEIR CRAPPY CARS IN ORDER TO FIX THIS KNOWN PROBLEM.  OWNERS ARE GETTING STUCK WITH A $1000-$2000 REPAIR BILL TO FIX THIS PROBLEM.

COULD NOT TURN THE WHEEL AT ALL, STEERING WAS OUT. THE VOICE COMMAND CAME ON  SAYING GET ASSISTANCE IMMEDIATELY.  THIS WAS REPEATED OVER AND OVER.  TURNED VEHICLE OFF, RE-STARTED AND IT WAS NOW WORKING.  I DROVE TO A SHOP THEY SAID THIS DOES HAPPEN WITH THIS YEAR MAYBE ONCE A YEAR.

I WAS DRIVING IN TRAFFIC WHEN THE ENGINE STARTED TO RUN ROUGH AND LOUD. I HAD TO PULL OVER AND TURN IT OFF. WHEN TRYING TO TURN IT BACK ON IT STARTED UP AND CONTINUED TO RUN ROUGH. I HAD THE VEHICLE TOWED TO THE SHOP. WHEN THEY LOOKED AT IT THEY TOLD ME THE ENGINE NEEDED TO BE REPLACED DUE TO THE TIMING CHAIN TENSIONER FAILING. WHEN I ASKED ABOUT WHEN I WAS SUPPOSED TO HAVE THIS SERVICE DONE THEY TOLD ME ITS NOT LISTED IN THE OWNERS MANUEL OR AT ANY SERVICE INTERVAL UP TO THIS POINT. THE PART IS NOT ON ANY LIST OF SERVICE FOR THE CAR YET FAILED AT 93K MILES. VW SHOULD ISSUE A RECALL FOR THIS PROBLEM BECAUSE THEY DIDN'T REPORT IT TO ME AS SOMETHING THAT COULD BREAK. I WAS TOLD WHEN I BOUGHT THE CAR THAT THE TIMING CHAIN AND TENSIONER SHOULD LAST THE LIFE OF THE VEHICLE WHICH SHOULD BE MUCH HIGHER THEN 93K. THIS IS A COMMON ISSUE IN ALL VW TSI ENGINES AND CAN HAPPEN AS EARLY AS 40K, VW NEEDS TO FIX THIS AND WARN EXISTING CUSTOMERS.

DSG TRANSMISSION MECHATRONICS UNIT FAILED AT 70,000 MILES JULY 2016. TRANSMISSION GOES INTO LIMP MODE...WON'T GO INTO REVERSE AND JUMPS DOWN TO AND REMAINS IN FIRST GEAR WHEN IN D.  ALL SERVICE DONE ON SCHEDULE.  MFR REFUSES TO COVER REPLACEMENT OF UNIT DUE TO LIMITED WARRANTY.

VEHICLE WAS STATIONARY AND PARKED.  IT WOULD NOT START.  THE ENGINE TRIED TO TURN OVER BUT WOULD NOT STAY RUNNING.  IT WAS TAKEN TO A VOLKSWAGEN DEALER SERVICE DEPARTMENT FOR DIAGNOSIS.  THE RESULT IS A TIMING CHAIN TENSIONER FAILURE AND VERY LARGE $2200 REPAIR FEE WITH THE POTENTIAL FOR A SIGNIFICANT REBUILD OF THE ENGINE IF MORE DAMAGE IS FOUND.  AFTER SOME RESEARCH IT APPEARS THAT THIS IS A KNOWN DESIGN ISSUE WITH THE TENSIONER PART AND THERE IS A TECHNICAL SERVICE BULLETIN (TSB 1512-01) ISSUED FOR IT BUT NO RECALL.  IT IS VERY LIKE TO OCCUR FOR ALL VOLKSWAGEN MODELS WITH THE 2.0 TSI ENGINE PRODUCED BETWEEN 2008-2013.  THIS COULD HAVE BEEN LIFE THREATENING IF THE FAILURE HAD OCCURRED WHILE THE VEHICLE WAS IN MOTION, ESPECIALLY AT HIGHER SPEEDS.

TIMING CHAIN TENSIONER FAILURE - THE CAR WAS PARKED FOR THE NIGHT. IN THE MORNING I WENT TO START IT. I WOULD NOT START. THERE WERE NO LIGHTS OR ERROR CODES. TOWED TO THE DEALERSHIP. THE DEALERSHIP STATED ZERO COMPRESSION AND BENT VALVES. THEY STATED I NEED A NEW ENGINE. 7400.00 CALLED VW OF AMERICAN. THEY OFFERED NO HELP WHAT SO EVER. VOLKSWAGEN OF AMERICA JUST KEEPS STATING THE CAR WAS OUT OF WARRANTY. THERE IS A TSB, MULTIPLE COMPLAINTS ON THE INTERNET REGARDING TIGUANS, GTI'S AND PASSATS. THIS ENGINE HAS HAD THIS PROBLEM HAPPENING FOR YEARS FROM 2008 TO 2013 VW WILL NOT ACCEPT ANY RESPONSIBILITY.

THIS IS A LOW MILEAGE (31,000) VEHICLE. UNEXPECTED, COMPLETE FAILURE OF RADIO, CD, NAVIGATION SYSTEM, BLUETOOTH HANDS-FREE COMMUNICATION... EVERYTHING WENT DEAD. VW DEALER CHECK FUSES AND RADIO FUSE AND SAID THAT THEY WERE OK. RADIO AND ALL FUNCTIONS ASSOCIATED WITH RADIO DEAD AND NOT WORKING. WILL NOT TURN ON. WHY IS THIS A SAFETY ISSUE? BECAUSE OF THE HANDS-FREE, BLUETOOTH PHONE CAPABILITIES NO LONGER WORK. VERY DANGEROUS. PLUS NAVIGATION DOESN'T WORK.

THE CAR SPUTTERED, SHOOK, AND MADE AN AWFUL SOUND SIMILAR TO A TON OF MARBLES IN A DRIER MACHINE. THE TIMING CHAIN WENT AT ROUGHLY 82,000 MILES. ACCORDING TO VW LITERATURE THEY STATED THAT THE REASON THEY WENT BACK TO A TIMING CHAIN IS THAT IT IS A LIFETIME, NONSERVICEABLE PART. THE TIMING CHAIN GOING ON AN INTERFERENCE TYPE ENGINE DESTROYED MY ENGINE TO THE ORDER OF ALMOST $4000. VW DID NOT WANT TO ASSIST WITH ANYTHING.

WE PURCHASED AND WE WERE SERVICING OUR VW GTI 2010 AT AUTOBARN MT. PROSPECT/IL.  IN THE LAST 2 YEARS WE REPLACED ALL IGNITION COILS AT DIFFERENT TIME INTERVALS AND TWICE FOR CYLINDER #2.  THERE ARE ACTUALLY MULTIPLE ISSUES HERE.  FIRST, THIS KIND OF PROBLEM CAN EASILY GENERATE AN ACCIDENT, IF ONE IGNITION COIL FAILS AT THE WRONG TIME AND THE WRONG PLACE (WHEN PASSING OR DRIVING ON A MOUNTAIN ROAD).  SECOND, THE IGNITION COILS ARE POORLY DESIGNED AND THEY GO BAD WAY TOO FAST MAKING THE CAR UNDRIVEABLE.  COSTLY TOWING WAS REQUIRED ALMOST EVERY TIME.  THIRD, THE VW DEALERSHIP SHOULD ADVISE CUSTOMERS TO REPLACE ALL COILS IN THE SAME TIME AT THE FIRST SIGN OF TROUBLE. INSTEAD THEY CHOOSE TO REPLACE THEM ONE BY ONE, CHARGING BETWEEN $180.00 AND $220.00 EVERY TIME JUST FOR LABOR, WHEN THE PART ITSELF COSTS JUST $32.00 AND THE LEVEL OF DIFFICULTY FOR THIS TASK IS VERY LOW.  *TR

I WAS TOLD THAT THE IGNITION COIL SHOULD LAST UP UNTIL 100K MILEAGE AND THIS GAVE OUT AT 65K AND CAUSED ENGINE MISFIRING AND ALMOST ENGINE FAILURE.  VOLKSWAGEN HAS SIMILAR RECALLS FOR THEIR IGNITION COILS AND I THINK THE 2010 VW GTI SHOULD BE INCLUDED.  THANK YOU.   *TR

VEHICLE WAS RUNNING VERY ROUGH.  HARD TO START.  HAD IT TOWED TO NORTH PENN VW. THEY DIAGNOSED IT AS A DEFECTIVE TIMING CHAIN TENSIONER. TWO MANAGERS AND A TECH SAID THE PART FAILED AND IT SHOULD NOT HAVE. THEY SAID IT WAS OF NO FAULT OF MY OWN.  THEY SUGGESTED I CONTACT VW SINCE IT WAS A DEFECTIVE PART. I DID AND THEY SAID THEY WOULD NOT BE ABLE TO HELP ME SINCE IT OUT OF WARRANTY. IT IS A KNOWN PROBLEM ON ALL 2010 VW'S.  THE DEALERSHIP ADMITTED IT AND THERE IS A SERVICE BULLETIN(TSB) ADDRESSING THE EXACT PART.  *TR

TL* THE CONTACT OWNED A 2010 VOLKSWAGEN GTI. WHILE DRIVING APPROXIMATELY 45 MPH, THE FRONT DRIVER SIDE TIRE BLEW OUT AND FORCED THE VEHICLE TO VEER TO THE LEFT. AS A RESULT, THE VEHICLE CRASHED INTO THE RETAINER WALL. THE FRONT DRIVER SIDE AIR BAG DEPLOYED, BUT THE SEAT BELT FAILED TO RETRACT. A POLICE REPORT WAS NOT FILED AND NO INJURIES WERE SUSTAINED. THE VEHICLE WAS DESTROYED. THE APPROXIMATE FAILURE MILEAGE WAS 55,000.

TL* THE CONTACT OWNS A 2010 VOLKSWAGEN GTI. WHILE IDLING AT A TRAFFIC LIGHT, THE ENTIRE INSTRUMENT PANEL ILLUMINATED AND SMOKE APPEARED FROM THE ENGINE COMPARTMENT. THE VEHICLE WAS TAKEN TO AN INDEPENDENT MECHANIC. THE TECHNICIAN STATED THAT THE STARTER MELTED DUE TO THE BATTERY BEING CRACKED AND ACID SPILLED ONTO THE ENGINE COMPARTMENT. THE WIRE BETWEEN THE BATTERY AND STARTER WERE MELTED. THE INDEPENDENT MECHANIC RECOMMENDED THAT THE VEHICLE SHOULD BE TAKEN TO THE DEALER. THE VEHICLE WAS NOT REPAIRED. THE MECHANIC AND THE AUTO INSURANCE COMPANY STATED THAT THE FAILURES WERE NOT CAUSED BY A FIRE. THE MANUFACTURER WAS NOTIFIED. THE APPROXIMATE FAILURE MILEAGE WAS 72,000.

WHEN I START MY CAR I GET A WARNING SAYING MULTIPLE LIGHTS (I.E. HEADLIGHT,TAILLIGHT,FOG LIGHTS) ARE BURNT OUT. THE AFFECTED LIGHT EVENTUALLY TURNS ON. THE FUSE FOR MY LIGHTS WAS BLOWN AND SCORCHED AND MY LOCAL DEALER SAID IT WAS A FAULTY FUSE BOX WHICH IS THE SAME BOX FROM THE TIGUAN WHICH HAS ALREADY BEEN RECALLED.  *TR
THE CAR STALLED AND LOST POWER WHILE DRIVING. NO POWER AND NO TIME TO ALLOW SAFELY TO MOVE THE CAR TO THE SHOULDER. ALMOST CAUSE A REAR END COLLISION. *TR

THE FIRST INCIDENT THAT I HAD WAS STARTING WITH THE CAR MAKING WEIRD NOISES THAT WERE COMING FROM THE ENGINE/TRANSMISSION WHEN THE CAR WOULD START.  IT IS HARD TO EXPLAIN THE NOISE, BUT IT SOUNDED LIKE SOMETHING WAS WINDING UP. I TOOK THE CAR TO DEALERSHIP. THEY WEREN'T ABLE TO ESTABLISH WHAT WAS WRONG WITH THE CAR.  CHECK ENGINE LIGHT DIDN'T COME ON, AND CAR DID NOT REPRODUCE THE SAME NOISE WHEN I TOOK IT TO THE DEALERSHIP.  I WAS TOLD THAT THEY COULDN'T SEE ANYTHING WRONG WITH THE CAR.  09/05/2013, MORE NOISE, AND THIS TIME WAS FOLLOWED BY HARD DOWNSHIFTS, AND HARD BUCKING.  EVERY TIME THE CAR WOULD ACCELERATE, OR IF YOU WERE COMING TO THE STOP, IT WOULD SHIFT HARD, CAR WOULD BUCK.  I WAS TOLD THAT THE DSG MECHATRONIC UNIT HAS FAILED. TRANSMISSION REPLACED   04/09/2014  MY WIFE WAS DRIVING THE CAR.  SPEED 45 TO 50 MPH.  SHE NOTICED THAT THE CAR WASN'T ABLE TO ACCELERATE. ENGINE WAS REVVING UP, BUT CAR WOULDN'T GO. PULLED OVER ON THE SHOULDER, BEFORE SOMEONE REAR ENDED HER.  SHE LOOKED AT THE DASH BOARD, AND SHE NOTICED THAT "D" WAS FLASHING.  SHE TOOK THE CAR TO DEALER TO SEE WHAT IS GOING ON. I WAS TOLD THAT A POWER SUPPLY RELAY WAS THE CAUSE OF THIS PROBLEM, AND IT WASN'T COVERED BY THE POWER TRAIN WARRANTY.  PART # 4H0-951-253-A RELAY  CAR WAS PICKED UP ON 04/24/2014  05/08/2014  I STOPPED AT THE RED LIGHT, WAS GOING TO MAKE A RIGHT TURN, BUT THE CAR WOULDN'T WANT TO ACCELERATE.  IT FELT LIKE IT WAS IN NEUTRAL.  ENGINE WAS REVVING, BUT CAR WOULDN'T MOVE.  I LOOKED AT THE DASH BOARD, AND "D" LIGHT WAS FLASHING.  I PULLED ONTO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD, SO I DON'T GET REAR ENDED.  I TRIED TO SELECT THE NEUTRAL GEAR, "N" WAS FLASHING.  EACH GEAR POSITION THAT I SELECTED WAS FLASHING. I DROVE THE CAR BACK TO DEALER, AND TOLD THEM WHAT HAVE HAPPENED.  CAR IS CURRENTLY AT THE DEALER.  *TR

TL* THE CONTACT OWNS A 2010 VOLKSWAGEN GTI. THE CONTACT STATED THAT THE CHECK ENGINE WARNING LAMP ILLUMINATED AND THE ENGINE STARTED TO SHUDDER AND MISFIRED. THE VEHICLE WAS TAKEN TO THE DEALER WHERE THE TECHNICIAN DIAGNOSED THAT THE INTAKE MANIFOLD NEEDED TO BE REPLACED AND ALL OF THE VALVES NEEDED TO BE CLEAN. THE MANUFACTURER WAS MADE AWARE OF THE FAILURE. THE VEHICLE WAS NOT REPAIRED. THE FAILURE MILEAGE WAS 63,000. THE CURRENT MILEAGE WAS 64,000.

I WAS DRIVING ON THE INTERSTATE AT ABOUT 60 MPH AND I HEARD A LOUD BANG, LIKE A GUN SHOT. issues.title: Carbon Buildup on Intake Valves
issues.description: Direct injection engines accumulate carbon deposits on intake valves over time, causing rough idle, misfires, and reduced performance. This is a common issue with TSI engines due to lack of fuel washing over intake valves.
issues.fix_description: Walnut blasting or chemical cleaning of intake valves, typically performed every 40,000-60,000 miles
issues.prevention: Use high quality fuel, occasional highway driving, consider catch can installation

issues.title: Timing Chain Tensioner Failure
issues.description: The timing chain tensioner can fail, causing timing chain stretch or jump, potentially leading to catastrophic engine damage. More common in earlier production years.
issues.fix_description: Replace timing chain, tensioner, and guides. May require engine rebuild if valves are damaged
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes with correct specification oil, avoid extended oil change intervals

issues.title: High Pressure Fuel Pump (HPFP) Failure
issues.description: The cam-driven high pressure fuel pump can fail, causing fuel starvation, poor performance, and potential engine damage from running lean.
issues.fix_description: Replace high pressure fuel pump and inspect cam follower for wear
issues.prevention: Use high quality fuel, avoid running tank extremely low

issues.title: Water Pump Failure
issues.description: Plastic impeller water pumps can fail prematurely, causing coolant leaks and potential engine overheating. Common failure point around 60,000-80,000 miles.
issues.fix_description: Replace water pump, thermostat, and coolant. Often done with timing belt service
issues.prevention: Regular coolant changes, monitor coolant levels, replace at recommended intervals

issues.title: PCV System Failure
issues.description: The PCV valve and diverter valve can fail, causing oil consumption, rough idle, and boost leaks. Commonly affects turbo performance.
issues.fix_description: Replace PCV valve, diverter valve, and associated vacuum lines
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, check PCV system during routine maintenance

issues.title: Turbocharger Wastegate Actuator Issues
issues.description: The turbocharger wastegate actuator can stick or fail, causing overboost or underboost conditions, affecting performance and potentially damaging the engine.
issues.fix_description: Clean or replace wastegate actuator, check vacuum lines and solenoid
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, allow turbo to cool down after driving

issues.title: Ignition Coil Failure
issues.description: Ignition coils can fail prematurely, causing misfires, rough running, and potential damage to catalytic converters if not addressed promptly.
issues.fix_description: Replace failed ignition coil(s) and spark plugs
issues.prevention: Replace spark plugs at recommended intervals, use OEM or high-quality aftermarket coils

issues.title: DSG Transmission Mechatronic Unit Failure
issues.description: The DSG transmission control unit (mechatronic) can fail, causing harsh shifts, transmission warning lights, and potential transmission damage.
issues.fix_description: Replace or rebuild mechatronic unit, reprogram transmission
issues.prevention: Regular DSG service every 40,000 miles, proper driving technique

issues.title: Intake Manifold Runner Flap Failure
issues.description: The intake manifold runner control flaps can break or stick, causing reduced performance and check engine lights. Plastic components can become brittle over time.
issues.fix_description: Replace intake manifold or runner control motor and flaps
issues.prevention: Regular maintenance, avoid aggressive driving when engine is cold

issues.title: Fuel Injector Carbon Buildup
issues.description: Direct injection fuel injectors can develop carbon buildup, causing poor fuel delivery, misfires, and reduced performance over time.
issues.fix_description: Clean or replace fuel injectors, perform fuel system cleaning
issues.prevention: Use top-tier gasoline, regular fuel system cleaning treatments

issues.title: Thermostat Housing Leak
issues.description: The plastic thermostat housing can develop cracks and leaks, causing coolant loss and potential overheating issues.
issues.fix_description: Replace thermostat housing, thermostat, and coolant
issues.prevention: Regular cooling system maintenance, check for leaks during oil changes

editorial.tagline: The refined hot hatch that grew up gracefully
editorial.hero_blurb: The Mk6 GTI represents Volkswagen's most mature interpretation of the hot hatch formula. With its EA888 turbo engine and refined chassis, it delivers genuine performance wrapped in everyday usability.
editorial.essence: The Mk6 GTI perfected the balance between comfort and performance that made the GTI legend. It's the thinking enthusiast's choice - sophisticated enough for daily duties yet thrilling when the road opens up.
editorial.heritage: Building on 35 years of GTI heritage, the Mk6 marked a significant evolution from its predecessor. Introduced in 2009, it featured Volkswagen's new EA888 engine architecture and represented the brand's commitment to refined performance during a period of global automotive sophistication.
editorial.design_philosophy: Volkswagen pursued understated aggression with the Mk6, emphasizing clean lines and purposeful details. The design philosophy centered on 'progressive refinement' - maintaining GTI DNA while elevating build quality and interior sophistication to premium standards.
editorial.motorsport_history: While not factory-raced extensively, the Mk6 GTI served as the foundation for numerous grassroots racing efforts and tuner builds. Its robust EA888 engine became a favorite in time attack and autocross circles, proving its performance potential beyond street driving.
editorial.engine_character: The EA888 TSI delivers smooth, linear power with minimal turbo lag. It's refined yet eager, producing a satisfying whoosh from the turbocharger and maintaining strong midrange torque that makes daily driving effortless while providing genuine excitement when pushed.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 6-speed manual offers precise, mechanical engagement with well-defined gates and a clutch that's perfectly weighted for both spirited driving and traffic duty. Shifts are deliberate and satisfying, though not quite as crisp as the best Japanese boxes.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The Mk6 strikes an exemplary balance between compliance and control. The XDS electronic differential works seamlessly to manage front-wheel-drive dynamics, while the suspension absorbs road imperfections without sacrificing cornering precision or driver feedback.
editorial.steering_feel: Electric power steering provides good weight and reasonable feedback, though purists miss the hydraulic feel of earlier GTIs. Turn-in is precise and predictable, with enough communication to inspire confidence in spirited driving situations.
editorial.brake_confidence: Strong, progressive brakes with excellent pedal feel inspire confidence. The system provides ample stopping power for the performance level, with good heat resistance during enthusiastic driving and linear response that's easy to modulate.
editorial.sound_signature: A purposeful but refined exhaust note with a subtle turbo whistle. The sound is more sophisticated than aggressive - perfectly suited to the car's mature character while still providing audible confirmation of the performance beneath.
editorial.ideal_owner: Perfect for the mature enthusiast who wants genuine performance without compromise. Ideal for those who appreciate German engineering refinement and need a car that excels in both daily commuting and weekend backroad adventures.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Not suited for those seeking raw, unfiltered driving thrills or maximum performance per dollar. Those wanting extensive factory customization options or the latest infotainment technology should look elsewhere.
editorial.buyers_summary: Focus on maintenance history, particularly carbon cleaning and timing chain tensioner health. The Mk6 rewards proper care with exceptional reliability and represents excellent value in today's hot hatch market.

expertReviews.title: 2010 VW MK 6 Golf GTI Review - The Goldilocks of The GTI's
pros: Practical hatchback with good cargo space
Affordable entry into performance cars (~$7,000 CAD)
cons: Some interior wear at high mileage
expertReviews.verdict: The Mark 6 GTI is described as the 'Goldilocks' of GTIs - taking what the Mark 5 did to reinvent the GTI and amplifying it into a timeless masterpiece. It's praised as an excellent daily driver that's fun, practical, and economical without luxury car headaches. Perfect for those wanting to enter the world of fun cars on a budget, offering great value at around $7,000 CAD.

expertReviews.title: Reviewing The 2013 Volkswagen Golf GTI Mk6 (Is This The ...)
cons: Very light and numb steering feel
Less exciting than Mk5 or Mk7 alternatives
Front-wheel drive struggles with high power
expertReviews.verdict: The Mk6 GTI delivers solid performance and comfort but suffers from numb steering and reliability concerns. While it drives well and maintains GTI DNA, the reviewer recommends the Mk5 for driving experience or Mk7 for daily use over this generation due to timing chain issues and less engaging character.

expertReviews.title: I review the underrated VW Golf GTI (the mk6 GTI) UK. how ...
pros: Great value compared to newer GTIs
Usable daily driver with dogs and everyday use
Analog driving experience without excessive electronics
Well-built interior with no rattles after 10+ years
Classic GTI styling that's not aggressive
Good sound through engine noise pipe
Narrow tires provide accessible handling limits
cons: Basic spec with no adaptive suspension or active exhaust
Interior looks dull and old-fashioned compared to newer models
Limited power compared to modern hot hatches
Not suitable for track use without modifications
Expensive for age compared to non-GTI Golf models
expertReviews.verdict: The Mk6 GTI is described as the most underrated Golf GTI and the last truly analog version. At around 10,000, it offers exceptional value compared to 40,000 Mk8 models. While slower than modern alternatives, it provides a pure, engaging driving experience with excellent daily usability. The reviewer emphasizes its comfort, build quality, and classic GTI character, making it ideal for enthusiasts wanting an authentic hot hatch experience without modern complexity.

expertReviews.title: MK6 VW Golf GTI Review - Too Unreliable?
cons: Not as engaging as manual competitors
expertReviews.verdict: The MK6 GTI is a competent hot hatch with good handling and comfort, but suffers from significant reliability issues including DSG problems and timing chain failures. While affordable and well-rounded, the reviewer finds it boring compared to alternatives like the Opel Astra OPC and suggests considering less popular competitors for better value.

expertReviews.title: 2010 Volkswagen Golf GTI MK6 Review | The forgotten GTI
pros: Comfortable daily driver with family practicality
210 HP with potential for more power when tuned
Xenon adaptive headlights and better equipment
cons: Double the price of Mark 5 GTI for minimal improvements
Limited availability due to short shelf life
expertReviews.verdict: The Mark 6 GTI is an underrated and forgotten generation that offers genuine improvements over the Mark 5, including better interior quality, comfort, and equipment. However, at nearly double the price of a Mark 5 for only 13 more horsepower and being essentially a facelift, many buyers find it hard to justify the cost. Japanese imports offer better condition but come with history concerns. It's a solid daily driver that balances performance and practicality well.

expertReviews.title: SHOULD YOU BUY A VW GOLF GTI MK6 IN 2023 ...
pros: Great fun factor and driver involvement
Good build quality with minimal rattles
Natural engine sound through hollow tube system
cons: Engine warning light common issue with inlet manifold
Basic spec compared to modern hot hatches
expertReviews.verdict: The Mk6 GTI represents exceptional value in 2023, offering the classic GTI experience at bargain prices. Owner's 5-year experience shows excellent reliability with minimal costs beyond basic maintenance. The car provides genuine driver engagement and fun without modern electronic interference. At 7.5-8k for higher mileage examples, it's described as a 'bargain of the century' that doesn't feel its age when driving. Highly recommended for those wanting an involving, reliable hot hatch at great value.
